a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.01ee802b-7055-42ab-ad46-94fd3c0a53b2.description=
Generate Run URL - Generates an href HTML link that contains a URL to the run history report for the current run.

Inputs\:
    variablename  - The name of the flow variable where the result should be stored.
Default value\: IC_ReportURL
    displaytext - The text to display for the href link. 
Default\: "Run History Report Available Here"

Results\:
    result - The untagged URL to the run report for the current run.
Example (with default values)\: IC_ReportURL ,Run History Report Available Here

Responses\:
    success - The flow completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The flow completed unsuccessfully.
a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.565662d0-6a3d-476c-ad99-0395b600cdd6.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.   
Does not return any results (only whether the command was executed)

Input Parameters\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name)
TNSEntry - the entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information
Username - username to connect as
Password - password
Command - the command to execute

Responses\:
more items - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
updateCount - the update count of the command executed

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below present the syntax to be used for having the same effect as the following PL/SQL script\:
BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}
a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.6a3ae4ce-f623-44fd-8c63-f9854cbfdd77.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.6af0ed00-c101-41d5-a974-e652ac596d8f.description=This workflow returns the component properties and values using Artifact APIs. result\: propertyNameValuesList\: pipe separated list of property name and values ( where each property name and values would be ; seprated and multiple values would be , seprated) e.g. - property 1; value1,value2|property 2; value3|property 3; value3,value4|........ a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.86169206-07ee-4b9b-b9f7-49ed982e80d9.description=
Runs a SQL query against an Oracle database, using the information in the tnsnames.ora file.  
The first row is returned on the first run of the operation. Subsequent calls with the same information return the other rows.

Inputs\:
    TNSPath -The path to the folder of the TNS file tnsnames.ora. This path must be accessible by the OO RAS service. For example, if the RAS and the Oracle server are installed on the same Windows system, the TNSPath might look like “C\:\app\Administrator\product\11.1.0\db_1\network\admin”. If the RAS and the Oracle server are on different Windows systems, you can copy the tnsnames.ora file  to the RAS system. The TNSPath might look like “C\:\Program Files\Hewlett-Packard\Operations Orchestration\RAS\Java\Default\webapp\conf” or “C\:\Temp” depending on where you place the .ora file. 
    TNSEntry - The entry name in the tnsnames.ora file that contains the connection information. For example, the value for the TNSEntry input is “TestEntry” if the content in the tnsnames.ora file looks like the following\: 

TestEntry \=
  (DESCRIPTION \=
   (ADDRESS \= (PROTOCOL \= TCP)(HOST \= 16.110.111.111)(PORT \= 1521))
   (CONNECT_DATA \=
     (SERVER \= DEDICATED)
     (SERVICE_NAME \= orcl)
   )
 )

    Username - The username to connect to the Oracle database. 
    Password - The password for the Username.
    Command - The command to execute. 
    Delimiter – The delimiter to use between the columns in the returnResult result.
    Key – The key to use to keep multiple query results distinct.
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution.
Default values\: 0 

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returned the data returned for each row separated by the value you specified in the Delimiter input (for example, “key16|lst|16”).
    columnNames - The names of the columns returned, separated by the value you specified in the Delimiter input (for example, “MYKEY|NAME|ID”).
    rowsLeft - The number of rows remaining that match the query. 

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - There was an error executing the command.

Notes\:
1. This operation only supports Oracle. 
2. This operation can only execute the "SELECT" statement. For statements that modify the database, use the TNS Names SQL Command operation.

Input Values\: vm.requester.email - The email address from the prior step result htmldocument - THe email body text from the prior result a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.b93e6523-8b12-42cf-b420-1ec977e47043.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.

Inputs\: _PROCESS_INSTANCE_ID - Process Instance Id _processInstanceState - Process Instance State (Use value from selection list CSA-ProcessInstance-State) Result\: _processInstanceState -Updated Process Instance State a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.description=This flow is used to request an IP address from EfficientIP in the production vlan of the chosen security zone and update the CCLUSTER table with the new IP address. The flow selects the cluster name from infradb which corresponds to the subscription id. The subflow IPAM_ReserveIPs performs an API call requesting a new IP address for the cluster name in the production vlan. The flow loops over all possible production vlans and tries to request an IP address. In case a subnet does not have free IP addresses anymore, the flow tries to request an IP address from the next available subnet that it queries from the VLANS table. After a successful request, the row in the CCLUSTER table is updated using the SQL query UPDATE CCLUSTER SET VIP\='${VIP}' WHERE VNAME\='${clusterName}' In case the SQL update fails, the IP address is released again and the flow terminates with an error.The cluster name and its IP address is also updated as a property in CSA to be later visible in the customer portal. Each virtual hostname for the cluster (cluster name or additional resource names) is visible in the portal property of flow. The cluster name is first virtual hostname and will be visible with number. In case of any failure during the deployment, a mail is sent to the requestor (as it is done in all MPC flows) and an error message sent to CSA. a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.e4b1e9c0-0125-46f1-8a35-92a3d89faeee.description=This workflow returns the component properties and values using Artifact APIs. result\: propertyNameValuesList\: pipe separated list of property name and values ( where each property name and values would be ; seprated and multiple values would be , seprated) e.g. - property 1; value1,value2|property 2; value3|property 3; value3,value4|........ a5a62af8-cf77-4bbc-8b48-c1dd0b5e841b.ecaf7678-3115-406c-8866-4aefffba5f5e.description=This flow with send an email notifying the Support team that the email notification to the creator failed. Input Values\: vm.requester.email - The email address from the prior step result htmldocument - THe email body text from the prior result
